    "body": "@andrewda You don't need a native module to get the mouse position.  If you think about it, when dragging your mouse will always be over the window.  You can implement code similar to this\n\n``` js\nimport { remote } from 'electron';\n\nlet wX;\nlet wY;\nlet dragging = false;\n\n$('.draggable').mousedown(function (e) {\n    dragging = true;\n    wX = e.pageX;\n    wY = e.pageY;\n});\n\n$(window).mousemove(function (e) {\n    e.stopPropagation();\n    e.preventDefault();\n    if (dragging) {\n        var xLoc = e.screenX - wX;\n        var yLoc = e.screenY - wY;\n\n        try {\n            remote.BrowserWindow.getFocusedWindow().setPosition(xLoc, yLoc);\n        } catch (err) {\n            console.log(err);\n        }\n    }\n});\n\n$(window).mouseup(function () {\n    dragging = false;\n});\n```\n\nExcuse the jQuery 😆 \n\nBut yeah, I've tested that on really slow machines moving the mouse stupidly fast and it has never failed me yet 👍 \n"
  },
